This is where we actually make our own TOC.

Used this plus guiguts template CSS for sonnets:

```
<table summary="Table of Contents">
```

Can use CSS like this to spread out ebook formatting if needed? At least, I used this on sonnets in PPV; maybe that one was an outlier though.

```
@media handheld {
  table {
    width: 96%;
    margin-left: 2%;
    margin-right: 2%;
  }
}
```

(This CSS spreads the TOC across the page instead of jamming it all toward the left margin.)

If there is a page marker in the middle of the TOC, just put the span inside the first `<td>` in the `<tr>` where it occurs. It will jam to the right margin, and hopefully the ebook version will use the proper location for the page jump.

Used this CSS for fisherboy:

```
img.drop-cap
{
  float: left;
  margin: 0 0.5em 0 0;
  height: 5em;
  width: auto;
}

p.drop-cap:first-letter,
p.drop-cap-narrow:first-letter,
p.drop-cap-wide:first-letter
{
  color: transparent;
  visibility: hidden;
}
p.drop-cap:first-letter {
  margin-left: -1.6em;
}
/* for narrow letters like I */
p.drop-cap-narrow:first-letter {
  margin-left: -1.25em;
}
/* for wider letters like W or M */
p.drop-cap-wide:first-letter {
  margin-left: -1.9em;
}
/* In case of a leading " - wrap it in a <span>
 * and keep the quote mark in the image. Will hide
 * it in the HTML version, using the graphic, but show it
 * in the handheld version as text.
 */
.drop-cap-hide {
  display: none;
}

@media handheld
{
  img.drop-cap
  {
    display: none;
  }

  p.drop-cap:first-letter,
  p.drop-cap-narrow:first-letter,
  p.drop-cap-wide:first-letter
  {
    color: inherit;
    visibility: visible;
    margin-left: 0;
  }
  .drop-cap-hide { display: inline; }
}

.upper-case {
    text-transform: uppercase;
}
```

```
<div>
  <img class="drop-cap" src="images/dropcapA.png" alt=""/>
</div>

<p class="drop-cap"><span class="upper-case">The</span>

<p class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap-hide">"</span><span class="upper-case">The</span>
```

Run the files through PPTools as a last check.

